ITALY08.12.2002

Journalist imprisoned over articles in 1960s.
Reporters sans fronti=E8res today expressed its outrage over the=
 imprisonment=20
of former journalist Stefano Surace (photo), 69, for supposed press crimes=
=20
committed more than 30 years ago.
The case is "doubly scandalous", Reporters Without Borders=20
secretary-general Robert M=E9nard said in a letter to Italian President=
 Carlo=20
Azeglio Ciampi. "To sentence journalists to imprisonment for press crimes=20
is contrary to UN standards, but it is unworthy of a democratic country to=
=20
jail an elderly man who has not been a journalist for years for crimes that=
=20
should be subject to limitation by lapse of time and which would nowadays=20
not even be the subject of prosecution," he said. "We call on you to=20
intervene and pardon Stefano Surace so that he can be released", the letter=
=20
added. "We also call for the removal of prison sentences for press crimes=20
from Italian law, as recommended by the UN Commission on Human Rights and=20
the UN Special Rapporteur on promotion and protection of the right to=20
freedom of opinion and expression."
Surace, who edited the nonconformist publication Le Ore during the 1960s,=20
has been incarcerated since December 2001 in Opera prison near Milan, where=
=20
he is serving a sentence of two years, six months and 12 days stemming from=
=20
convictions for libel and obscenity handed down in 1963 and 1967. A=20
resident of France for almost 40 years, he was arrested when he went to=20
visit a friend in Italy.
He was known for his investigations into prison life and, while still a=20
journalist, had founded an association of former detainees. He had ceased=20
to work as a journalist before these convictions and had become a ju-jitsu=
=20
teacher.

